        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New York</placeName> <date>September 22d 1853</date></p>
			<p><addressee>Isaac Leeser Esqr</addressee></p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(3)">Seeing that your<lb/> Bible translation will be finished this month&#44; I would<lb/> respectfully request you to forward to me one copy<lb/> bound in morocco gilt Edges &#40;No 3&#41; at &#36;5 extra.<lb/> with my name attached to it in full&#44; also one copy<lb/> of your daily Prayer books&#44; strongly bound with<lb/> &#8220;<persName>Lewis A. Arnold</persName>&#8221; printed on the cover&#44; and<lb/> one copy of your Day of Atonement Books.<lb/> Please include Bill for Occident.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I suppose you have heard of the death<lb/> of my father&#44; who departed this life on the<lb/> <date>7<hi rend="sup">th</hi> of August</date> last at <placeName>Jebenhausen</placeName> after only<lb/> 2 days illness&#44; aged not quite 72 years.</p>
			<p>This sad news came quite sudden upon me<lb/> having received a letter from my lamented father<lb/> only about 3 weeks ago&#44; written in the best of<lb/> spirits&#44; and dated <date>August 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date>&#44; the very day<lb/> he was taken sick. Believe me&#44; dear Sir&#33;<lb/> I feel his loss severely&#44; he was always a good<lb/> father to me&#44; and although not possessing the<lb/> advantages of a liberal education&#44; he was always<lb/> alive to every thing advancing or improving<lb/> our holy religion. Very few men in his<lb/> neighborhood left a better name for benevolence.</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>May His soul rest in peace Amen.</p>
			<p>And now my friend&#44; I have to trouble you to<lb/> answer me a religious question&#44; which has<lb/> occupied my mind lately. Since I have been<lb/> in business in this city&#44; I have with the help<lb/> of God been a strict observer of our holy <add>Hebrew</add>.<lb/> This of course is no credit to any one professing<lb/> Judaism&#44; but you know human nature well<lb/> enough to appreciate the sacrifice of worldly<lb/> considerations one has to undergo who has been <lb/>delinquent in this great duty towards his<lb/> maker. I come now to the point.<lb/> Notwithstanding observing the <add>Hebrew</add> strictly&#44;<lb/> I have at the same time kept but the 1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> day<lb/> of the holy days <add>Hebrew</add>&#44; and in<lb/> doing so&#44; I felt myself fully justified&#44; as<lb/> the plain Law of God only commands us to<lb/> keep each one of these respective days holy&#44;<lb/> and we have no authority to change it in 2 days&#44;<lb/> as it is written in the same Law of God on several<lb/> occasions &#8220;Ye shall not add unto the word<lb/> which I command thee&#44; neither shall ye diminish<lb/> ought from it.&#8221; Now my dear friend&#44; how do<lb/> you reconcile these several passages to this<lb/> rabbinical institution of ordaining two days<lb/> in place of the highest authority commanding<lb/> only one&#63; This is my position and argument.</p>
		<pb n="3"/>
			<p>I have never studied traditional law&#44; and as<lb/> it is my wish to do right in the sight of<lb/> God and men&#44; I take my refuge to you&#44;<lb/> to inform me on this subject&#44; <sic>wether</sic> the<lb/> step I have taken is right or wrong.<lb/> Judging from your past strict Orthodoxy&#44;<lb/> I am almost convinced beforehand&#44; that you<lb/> will decide against me&#44; however I have<lb/> full reliance in your Judgment confident<lb/> that you will give me sufficient proofs to<lb/> uphold your position&#44; at the same time<lb/> considering the consistency of my own opinion<lb/> in this matter.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I will say it without meaning<lb/> any flattery to yourself&#44; that your teaching<lb/> has somewhat made me a better man&#44;<lb/> and in accordance will with pleasure<lb/> subject myself to any decision you shall<lb/> be pleased to pronounce</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">May I beg of you the favor of as early a<lb/> reply as your occupation will permit.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Wishing you many happy returns<lb/> to the approaching holy days&#44; I remain</p>
          <p rend="indent(8)">most respectfully&#44; your friend</p>
          <p rend="indent(9)"><persName role="author">Lazarus Rinold</persName></p>
			<p><placeName>40 Cedar St</placeName></p>
		<pb n="4"/>
			<p><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
